{
  "texts": [
    "Reference missions and architectures A successful exploration mission requires spacecraft to change their velocity (also called △V maneuvers) in order to follow precise trajectories.",
    "Velocity change requirements are derived from orbital and spaceflight mechanics, involving the balance of propulsive, gravitational, and aerodynamic forces when entering the atmosphere of planets.",
    "The propulsive forces are produced by the spacecraft engine.",
    "Propellants are grouped into storable and cryogenic propellants.",
    "The main difference is the achievable specific impulse I sp or thrust per unit mass flow rate, which is defined as the ratio between the thrust and the product of mass flow rate and the gravitational acceleration constant."
  ]
}